---
/**
 * /case-studies/sca-headless-cms/process — AI workflow + Type 2 fun + decision trail.
 */
export const prerender = true

import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import CaseStudyHero from '../../../components/case-study/CaseStudyHero.astro'
import TableOfContents from '../../../components/case-study/TableOfContents.astro'
import Aside from '../../../components/case-study/Aside.astro'
import ReadingProgress from '../../../components/ReadingProgress.astro'

const TOC = [
  { href: '#verification', label: 'The verification stack' },
  { href: '#provenance', label: 'Provenance metadata' },
  { href: '#alt-text-afternoon', label: 'The alt-text afternoon' },
  { href: '#agent-toolkit', label: 'The agent-toolkit gap' },
  { href: '#decisions', label: 'The decision trail' },
  { href: '#adrs', label: 'ADRs as insurance' },
]

const provenanceSnippet = `provenance: {
  author: "Ed O'Connell",
  generatedBy: 'AI-assisted with human authorship and review',
  reviewedBy: "Ed O'Connell",
  context: 'Sanity-backed article draft',
  date: '2026-05-07',
}`

const PAGE_TITLE = 'The Process'
const PAGE_DESC =
  'SCA Headless CMS — how I work with AI assistance, what I verify by hand, the agent-toolkit issue I filed, and where the friction was.'

const canonicalUrl = new URL(Astro.url.pathname, Astro.site ?? 'https://edoconnell.org').href
const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: PAGE_TITLE,
  description: PAGE_DESC,
  url: canonicalUrl,
  mainEntityOfPage: canonicalUrl,
  datePublished: '2026-05-07',
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: "Ed O'Connell", url: 'https://edoconnell.org' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Person', name: "Ed O'Connell", url: 'https://edoconnell.org' },
  isPartOf: {
    '@type': 'CreativeWork',
    name: 'SCA Headless CMS',
    url: 'https://edoconnell.org/case-studies/sca-headless-cms',
  },
}
---

<BaseLayout title={PAGE_TITLE} description={PAGE_DESC}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <ReadingProgress />

  <article class="cs">
    <p class="cs-breadcrumb">
      <a href="/case-studies/sca-headless-cms">SCA Headless CMS</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span>The process</span>
    </p>

    <CaseStudyHero
      title="The Process"
      date="2026-05-07"
      eyebrow="Case Study · Workflow · Springfield Commonwealth Academy"
    >
      <Fragment slot="lede">
        AI generates code and prose. <em>Verification is the part I don't delegate.</em>
        What that means in practice, what got documented along the way, and where the
        friction landed.
      </Fragment>
    </CaseStudyHero>

    <TableOfContents entries={TOC} />

    <section class="cs-section" id="verification">
      <p class="cs-section__num">01<small>Verification</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">The verification stack</h2>
      <p>
        AI is good at generation. It is uneven at telling you when its output is wrong. The
        verification stack exists because that asymmetry is real, not philosophical.
      </p>
      <p>What runs, in order of cost:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>astro check</code> — TypeScript shape errors, instant.</li>
        <li>
          <code>axe-core</code> via Playwright — accessibility regressions across mobile,
          tablet, desktop.
        </li>
        <li>
          Per-page Playwright spec — this case study has its own, asserting required
          headings, correct JSON-LD, no forbidden internal vocabulary, no console errors.
        </li>
        <li>Lighthouse CI — thresholds at 95+ for accessibility and best practices.</li>
        <li>
          Manual GROQ reads when something looks suspicious in HTML. Stega encoding hides
          things that read clean.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of this is unusual. Treating it as the floor and not the ceiling is the part I'm
        careful about.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="cs-pullquote">
        <p>Generation that doesn't pass the floor doesn't ship.</p>
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <Aside label="Working rules" variant="neutral">
      <p>
        A few outtakes from the verification rules. Each one rules out a mistake I have made
        before:
      </p>
      <ol class="cs-outtakes">
        <li>"Inferences cannot be premises for action."</li>
        <li>"Mechanical operations do not verify outcomes."</li>
        <li>"The read is the test that justifies the write."</li>
        <li>"Stale documents are inferences."</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Every mutation needs a verification step that justifies it. The shape of the rule
        outlasts the specific incident that taught it.
      </p>
    </Aside>

    <section class="cs-section" id="provenance">
      <p class="cs-section__num">02<small>Provenance</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">Provenance metadata</h2>
      <p>
        In this content model, Sanity-backed articles and demos can carry a
        <code>provenance</code> object — author, generator, reviewer, context, date. The
        object is visible in the Studio, queryable via GROQ, and visible in source maps when
        stega encoding is on. The case for it is simple: the origin of the content is part
        of the content.
      </p>
      <p>A representative shape:</p>
      <pre class="cs-code"><code>{provenanceSnippet}</code></pre>
      <p>
        This isn't a watermark. It's a queryable shape. A future filter — "show me every
        Sanity-backed document that was AI-drafted but not yet AI-reviewed" — is a one-line
        GROQ change, not a project. The right time to commit to this kind of metadata is at
        authoring, when the data is fresh; the wrong time is later, when you have to backfill.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="cs-section" id="alt-text-afternoon">
      <p class="cs-section__num">03<small>Agent at work</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">The alt-text afternoon</h2>
      <p>
        Late spring 2026. A schema validation pass (ADR-024 added
        <code>rule.required().warning(...)</code> on alt-text fields) flagged missing alt
        on dozens of image-bearing documents — news posts, hero images, program pages.
        Filling it by hand would have meant clicking through every document in the Studio,
        every photo, every byline.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sanity's content agent did it in one pass. A few minutes of agent-generated alt text
        against the actual image content, a few more of human review against the school's
        brand voice, then publish across the site.
      </p>
      <blockquote class="cs-pullquote">
        <p>"That would have taken me all day," the VP of marketing said when it finished.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        The speed mattered. The bigger thing was that an editor — not the engineer who set
        up the agent — watched it run, reviewed each generation against the school's brand,
        and signed off. Agent-driven content that an editor can review in real time gets
        used. Agent-driven content the editor can't review doesn't ship.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="cs-section" id="agent-toolkit">
      <p class="cs-section__num">04<small>Behavior gap</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">The agent-toolkit gap</h2>
      <p>
        Sanity's agent-toolkit MCP server has a tool called
        <code>patch_document_from_markdown</code>. The tool's stated purpose is to apply a
        markdown patch to a document. What it actually did, on the documents I tested, was
        rewrite the prose silently — same general shape, different sentences, in a voice that
        wasn't the voice of the source. There was no diff returned that disclosed the
        rewrite.
      </p>
      <p>
        I caught it because the resulting prose didn't sound like the original. The fact that
        I noticed at all is the lucky case; the unlucky case is publishing rewritten content
        without realizing.
      </p>
      <p>
        I filed it upstream as
        <a href="https://github.com/sanity-io/agent-toolkit/issues/20" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          sanity-io/agent-toolkit issue #20
        </a>. The framing in the issue is what it should be: a documented behavior gap, not
        a found bug. The tool's authors get to decide whether the gap is a defect or a
        documentation problem; I'm only responsible for naming what I observed and where.
      </p>
      <p>
        For my own pipeline, the workaround is to author Portable Text by hand in a script
        instead of going through the markdown route. Slower; safer; reproducible. Examples
        live alongside this site's content scripts.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Aside label="Type 2 fun">
      <p>
        Visual Editing across origins, when the embedded Studio sits on the same domain as
        the frontend but the iframe needs an authenticated session. Stega encoding showing up
        inside string equality checks because I forgot to <code>stegaClean()</code>. The
        agent-toolkit silent rewrite that took two sessions of debugging because the prose
        looked plausible. None of these were on the planning doc.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sanity's culture page calls that <em>Type 2 fun</em> — friction is part of the work,
        and the reward shows up in retrospect. Most of the things I learned about this stack,
        I learned from one of these moments. Each one became documentation, an upstream
        filing, or a script that someone else can reuse.
      </p>
    </Aside>

    <section class="cs-section" id="decisions">
      <p class="cs-section__num">05<small>Decisions</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">The decision trail</h2>
      <p>
        Why migrate at all: editor velocity and a content layer that could outlast a single
        site design. Editors waited on a marketing contractor for routine copy changes. There
        was no way to ship a new content type without rebuilding the page that displayed it.
        The site looked fine. Underneath, it was inert.
      </p>
      <p>
        Why headless specifically: separation of concerns. A schema editors can use, a query
        language engineers can use, and a render layer that can target a website today and
        something else tomorrow without a rewrite of the source.
      </p>
      <p>
        Why Sanity in particular: Portable Text. Sanity's structured-content philosophy
        treats prose as a typed array of blocks rather than an opaque HTML blob. That means
        AI agents can read and write it; that means the same content can render to a web
        page, an OG card, a search index, a JSON-LD payload — without rewriting it. GROQ is
        the second reason: SQL-shaped retrieval over typed documents. The third reason is
        Visual Editing — click-to-edit overlays that work without a custom CMS UI. None of
        these is unique to Sanity, but Sanity's combination is what felt right for a small
        team that needed both editor velocity and content-as-data.
      </p>
      <p>
        WordPress was a real alternative — easier ramp, larger ecosystem, broader hireable
        skill base. The
        <a href="https://www.springfieldcommonwealthacademy.org/admin/pricing">pricing page</a>
        names the trade-off honestly: the platforms are roughly cost-comparable for a site
        this size. What you give up by choosing WordPress is the structured layer
        underneath. What you give up by choosing Sanity is the breadth of plugin ecosystem.
        For a school site whose content has a future beyond the current site design, the
        first trade-off was worth more.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="cs-section" id="adrs">
      <p class="cs-section__num">06<small>Decision records</small></p>
      <h2 class="cs-section__title">ADRs as insurance</h2>
      <p>
        Every architectural decision lives in a single <code>decisions.md</code> file in the
        repo. Each entry includes context, options considered, the choice, and — when
        applicable — reversal instructions: what would need to change to undo this decision
        and what the cost of the undo would be.
      </p>
      <p>
        ADRs are usually presented as discipline. They're really insurance. The cost of
        writing them is twenty minutes; the cost of not writing them is finding out, three
        months later, why you can't change something obvious. Most of the deferred items on
        this project are deferred precisely because their ADRs document why now isn't the
        right moment, and the cost of revisiting later is small because the reasoning is
        captured.
      </p>
      <p>
        For an interview audience: every claim on this page can be traced backward to an
        ADR or a commit. The
        <a href="/case-studies/sca-headless-cms#proof">evidence section on the overview</a>
        is the public-facing surface; the repo is the source of truth.
      </p>
    </section>

    <footer class="cs-footer">
      <p class="cs-footer__nav">
        <a href="/case-studies/sca-headless-cms/build">Read the build →</a>
        <a href="/case-studies/sca-headless-cms">← Back to overview</a>
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  @import '../../../styles/case-study.css';
</style>
